REQUESTING PHYSICIAN: STEPHEN STRUP
REASON FOR EXAMINATION/PROCEDURE: BPH 

EXAMINATION / PROCEDURE:
CT UROGRAPHY Mar 24 2015  - 16:45




CLINICAL INDICATION:
BPH

TECHNIQUE: 
Multiple pre-contrast axial CT images were obtained from lower chest 
through pubic symphysis, followed by multiple axial CT images of abdomen 
and pelvis following split bolus administration of IV contrast, Omnipaque 
300, the mL. 
Reformatted images in the coronal and sagittal planes were generated from 
the axial data set to facilitate diagnostic accuracy.

TOTAL DLP (Dose-Length Product):  2205 mGy-cm.  Please note:  The 
reported value represents the total of one or more individual components 
during the CT acquisition on this date and at this time, and as such, the 
same value may appear in more than one CT report depending on the 
interpreting/reporting physicians.

COMPARISON:
None 

FINDINGS:
Kidneys, Ureters, Bladder:  The kidneys are normal in size and position 
demonstrating symmetric enhancement and excretion of contrast material. 
No renal or ureteral calculus. No secondary signs of urinary tract 
obstruction. No suspicious renal mass. No urothelial filling defect is 
identified. Incomplete contrast filling of the bladder, limiting 
assessment. No definite bladder wall thickening.

Lower chest:  Clear lung bases.

Liver, gallbladder, biliary tract:  No suspicious hepatic mass. 
Decompressed gallbladder. Borderline common duct dilatation.

Spleen:  Normal size spleen with calcified granulomas.

Pancreas:  Homogeneous attenuation without duct dilatation.

Adrenal glands:  No adrenal nodule.

Lymph Nodes:  No enlarged lymph nodes. 

GI Tract:  No thickened or dilated small or large bowel.

Mesentery/Peritoneum:  No suspicious nodule.

Pelvic Viscera:  Symmetric seminal vesicles. Nonspecific prostate 
calcifications. Overall prostate size within normal limits.

Free Fluid:  No significant free fluid.

Musculoskeletal and body wall:  No aggressive body wall or osseous 
findings.  

IMPRESSION: 
No renal calculus or suspicious renal/urothelial mass.

CRITICAL RESULT:  
No. 

COMMUNICATION:
Per this written report.
